":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places so called, especially Ashton-under-Lyne near Manchester. Most are named from Old English <i>æsc</i> ‘ash tree’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’; the one in Northamptonshire is <i>(æt thǣm) æscum</i> ‘(at the) ash trees’. Others have been assimilated to this from different sources. The one in Devon is ‘the settlement (<i>tūn</i>) of Æschere’, while the one in Hertfordshire is ‘the settlement of Ælli’."],"variants":[{"name":"Aspden","meanings":["English: habitational name from Aspden (alias Aspen) in Oswaldtwistle, Lancashire. This surname has been confused with   Ashton   and   Austin  , and probably also with   Aston   and   Astin  , all of which are common surnames in Lancashire."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":25,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Alice Ashton was born in 1430, in Croston, Lancashire, England as the daughter of Sir Ralph Ashton. She had at least 2 daughters with Sir William Farrington, Knight. She died about 1485, in Lancashire, England, at the age of 56."},"et":{"1430–Abt 1485":"1430–umbes 1485","1430–1485":"1430–1485","1440–1501":"1440–1501","1465–1510":"1465–1510","1475–1510":"1475–1510","1421–1486":"1421–1486","1501":"1501","1455":"1455","1510":"1510","1465":"1465","Abt 1475":"umbes 1475","1421":"1421","Abt 1485":"umbes 1485","1486":"1486","1475":"1475","1430":"1430","1485":"1485","1440":"1440","Leyland, Lancashire, England":"Leyland, Lancashire, England","Croston, Lancashire, England":"Croston, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"1430–Abt 1485":"1430–noin 1485","1430–1485":"1430–1485","1440–1501":"1440–1501","1465–1510":"1465–1510","1475–1510":"1475–1510","1421–1486":"1421–1486","1501":"1501","1455":"1455","1510":"1510","1465":"1465","Abt 1475":"noin 1475","1421":"1421","Abt 1485":"noin 1485","1486":"1486","1475":"1475","1430":"1430","1485":"1485","1440":"1440","Leyland, Lancashire, England":"Leyland, Lancashire, England","Croston, Lancashire, England":"Croston, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"1430–Abt 1485":"1430–environ 1485","1430–1485":"1430–1485","1440–1501":"1440–1501","1465–1510":"1465–1510","1475–1510":"1475–1510","1421–1486":"1421–1486","1501":"1501","1455":"1455","1510":"1510","1465":"1465","Abt 1475":"environ 1475","1421":"1421","Abt 1485":"environ 1485","1486":"1486","1475":"1475","1430":"1430","1485":"1485","1440":"1440","Leyland, Lancashire, England":"Leyland, Lancashire, Angleterre","Croston, Lancashire, England":"Croston, Lancashire, An